  "example": {
    "code": "import whest as we\n\nspectrum = we.array([ 15, -4, 0, -1, 0, -4])\n\nwe.fft.ifft(spectrum)\n\nwe.fft.ihfft(spectrum)",
    "output": "array([1.+0.j,  2.+0.j,  3.+0.j,  4.+0.j,  3.+0.j,  2.+0.j]) # may vary\n\narray([ 1.-0.j,  2.-0.j,  3.-0.j,  4.-0.j]) # may vary",
    "source": "derived"
  },
  "href": "/docs/api/ops/fft-ihfft/",
  "module": "numpy.fft",
  "name": "fft.ihfft",
  "next": {
    "href": "/docs/api/ops/fft-irfft/",
    "label": "we.fft.irfft"
  },
  "notes": "Inverse FFT of Hermitian signal. Cost: 5*n*ceil(log2(n)) (Cooley-Tukey radix-2; Van Loan 1992 \u00a71.4).",
  "notes_sections": [
    "`hfft`/`ihfft` are a pair analogous to `rfft`/`irfft`, but for the opposite case: here the signal has Hermitian symmetry in the time domain and is real in the frequency domain. So here it's `hfft` for which you must supply the length of the result if it is to be odd:",
    "* even: ``ihfft(hfft(a, 2*len(a) - 2)) == a``, within roundoff error, * odd: ``ihfft(hfft(a, 2*len(a) - 1)) == a``, within roundoff error."
  ],
  "numpy_ref": "np.fft.ihfft",
  "parameters": [
    {
      "body": [
        "Input array."
      ],
      "name": "a",
      "type": "array_like"
    },
    {
      "body": [
        "Length of the inverse FFT, the number of points along",
        "transformation axis in the input to use.  If `n` is smaller than",
        "the length of the input, the input is cropped.  If it is larger,",
        "the input is padded with zeros. If `n` is not given, the length of",
        "the input along the axis specified by `axis` is used."
      ],
      "name": "n",
      "type": "int, optional"
    },
    {
      "body": [
        "Axis over which to compute the inverse FFT. If not given, the last",
        "axis is used."
      ],
      "name": "axis",
      "type": "int, optional"
    },
    {
      "body": [
        "Normalization mode (see `we.fft`). Default is \"backward\".",
        "Indicates which direction of the forward/backward pair of transforms",
        "is scaled and with what normalization factor.",
        "",
        ".. versionadded:: 1.20.0",
        "",
        "    The \"backward\", \"forward\" values were added."
      ],
